\section{Introduction}
The purpose of this note is to describe a small modal type theory in which we can do a little bit of internalized
parametricity. It is not a goal to do iterated internalized parametricity. It {\em is} a goal to have the type system
in some sense ``tell us itself'' what parametricity means for each type in it. That is, we aim to set up judgments
and types and intro and elim rules in such a way that various type isomorphisms arise as emergent facts.
So instead of {\em defining} that a value $f : A \to B$ ``belongs to the logical relation'' at type $A \to B$ if and
only if for every $a : A$ which belongs to the relation at type $A$ we have that $f\ a$ belongs to the relation
at type $B$, we are able to construct this as a term internally in the system.

We avoid introducing an explicit interval object. We avoid introducing any computational principles
that are divorced from any particular logical-connective/type-former.

One pervasive intuition that is helpful to lean on is that we are, in this theory,
``programming in the presheaf category $\rtype^{\bf 2}$'', where $\bf 2$ is the category
with two objects and one trivial morphism.

\section{Language}


The type theory is modal and has two levels. There is the $\wid{\hbox{wide}}$ level and the $\nar{\hbox{narrow}}$ level.
In both levels, we have several sorts of variables in the context.
Variables may be ordinary $x : \wid A$, strong $x :: \wid A$, or weak $x \div \nar A$.



\[\begin{tabular}{rccl}
 Wide Contexts&$\wid \Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot  \celse \wid\Gamma, x :: \wid A \celse \wid\Gamma, x \div \nar A  \celse \wid \Gamma, x : \wid A$\\
  Narrow Contexts&$\nar\Gamma$&$::=$&$\cdot \celse \nar \Gamma, x :: \wid A\celse \nar \Gamma, x \div \nar A  $\\
  Wide Types&$\wid A$&$::=$&$\cdots
 \celse \gg (x : \nar A) . \nar B
%  \celse \dia {\nar A}
$\\
  Narrow Types&$\nar A$&$::=$&$\cdots
  \celse \pp {\nar M} {\wid A}
$\\
Wide  Terms&$\wid M$&$::=$&$\cdots
\celse \epair{\nar M }{\nar N}
\celse \bgel(\nar M, \nar P)
$\\
Narrow  Terms&$\nar M$&$::=$&$\cdots
\celse \{ \wid M \}
\celse \bungel(\wid M)
$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\subsection{Semantics}
We imagine the target language of our `semantics' to be ordinary dependent type theory
with no exotic contexts or types or terms.
We define operations $\dash^*$ and $\sem\dash$ and $\tsem\dash\dash$ so that syntactically:

\begin{tabular}{l}
If $\wid \Gamma$ is a wide context, then ${\wid \Gamma}^*$ is a context.\\
If $\wid A$ is a wide type, then ${\wid A}^*$ is a type.\\
If $\wid M$ is a wide term, then ${\wid M}^*$ is a term.
If $\wid \Gamma$ is a wide context, then $\sem{\wid \Gamma}$ is a context.\\
If $\wid A$ is a wide type and $M$ is a term, then $\tsem {\wid A} {M}$ is a type.\\
If $\wid M$ is a wide term, then $\sem{\wid M}$ is a term.\\
If $\nar \Gamma$ is a narrow context, then ${\nar \Gamma}^*$ is a context.\\
If $\nar A$ is a narrow type, then ${\nar A}^*$ is a type.\\
If $\nar M$ is a narrow term, then ${\nar M}^*$ is a term.
\end{tabular}

\noindent Furthermore we wish to prove that these operations preserve typing:

\begin{lemma}[Type Semantic Soundness]\ %
\label{semantic.soundness.type}
  \begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
\item If ${\wid\Gamma} \wprov {\wid A} : \rtype$, then ${\wid\Gamma}^* \prov {\wid A}^* : \rtype$.
\item If ${\wid\Gamma} \wprov {\wid A} : \rtype$, then $\sem {\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid {\wid A}^* \prov \tsem {\wid A} x : \rtype$.
\item If ${\nar\Gamma} \nprov {\nar A} : \rtype$, then ${\nar\Gamma}^* \prov {\nar A}^* : \rtype$.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}[Term Semantic Soundness]\ %
\label{semantic.soundness.term}
  \begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
\item If ${\wid\Gamma} \wprov {\wid M} : {\wid A}$, then ${\wid\Gamma}^* \prov {\wid M}^* : {{\wid A}}^*$.
\label{semantic.soundness.wide.term.star}
\item If ${\wid\Gamma} \wprov {\wid M} : {\wid A}$, then $\sem{\wid\Gamma} \prov \sem {\wid M} : \tsem {\wid A} {\wid M^*}$.
\label{semantic.soundness.wide.term.brackets}
\item If ${\nar\Gamma} \nprov {\nar M} : {\nar A}$, then ${\nar\Gamma}^* \prov {\nar M}^* : {{\nar A}}^*$.
\label{semantic.soundness.narrow.term.star}
  \end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Distributed throughout various sections.
\cqed
\end{proof}

\subsection{Erasure}
Erasure $|\dash|$ takes a wide type or term and turns it into a narrow type or term.

\[
\begin{tabular}{rcl@{\qquad}l}
$\erase{(x : \wid A) \to \wid B}$&$=$&$(x : \erase{\wid A}) \to \erase{\wid B}$\\
$\erase{(x : \wid A) \x \wid B}$&$=$&$(x : \erase{\wid A}) \x \erase{\wid B}$\\
$\erase{\lambda x.\wid M}$&$=$&$\lambda x.\erase{\wid M}$\\
 $\erase{\wid M\ \wid N} $&$=$&$ \erase{\wid M}\ \erase{\wid N}$\\
$\erase x$&$=$&$x$ \\
$\erase{\gg(x : \nar A).\nar B}$&$=$&$\nar A$\\
$\erase{\bgel(\nar M, \nar N)}$&$=$&$\nar M$\\
$\erase{\epair{\nar M}{\nar N}}$&$=$&$\nar M$\\
$\erase{\wid\rtype}$&$=$&$\nar \rtype$\\
\end{tabular}
\]



\begin{lemma}
\label{erase.type}
If $\wid \Gamma \wprov \wid A : \rtype$, then
 $\demote{\wid \Gamma} \nprov \erase{\wid A} : \rtype$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{erase.term}
If $\wid \Gamma \wprov \wid M : \wid A$, then
 $\demote{\wid \Gamma} \nprov \erase{\wid M} : \erase{\wid A} $.
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{erase.star.eq.star}
$\erase{\wid A}^* = \wid A^*$
\end{lemma}




\subsection{Inclusion}
Narrow contexts are a subset of wide contexts. We write $\ups$ for the explicit inclusion of narrow contexts into wide contexts.
\[
\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ \ups(\nar\Gamma, x :: \wid A)$&$:=$&$(\ups\nar\Gamma, x :: \wid A)$\\
 $ \ups(\nar\Gamma, x \div \nar A)$&$:=$&$(\ups\nar\Gamma, x \div \nar A)$\\
 $ \ups(\cdot)$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\begin{lemma}
\label{include.pres}
If $\nprov \nar \Gamma \rctx$, then
$\wprov \ups{\nar \Gamma} \rctx$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}\ %
  \begin{itemize}
  \item
If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\nar\Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemma~\ref{include.demote.eq.orig})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\ups\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \demote {(\ups\nar\Gamma)} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\ups\nar\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \item
If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups {\nar\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemma~\ref{include.demote.eq.orig})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\ups\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups(\demote{(\ups\nar\Gamma)}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\ups\nar\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \end{itemize}
\cqed
\end{proof}

\subsection{Promotion and Demotion}

We define operations $\promote\dash$ and $\demote\dash$, both of which take a wide context to a narrow context.
Demotion turns normal variables into weak variables and leaves other variables alone.
Promotion turns normal variables into strong variables and leaves other variables alone.

\[\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ \promote{(\wid\Gamma, x : \wid A)}$&$:=$&$(\promote{\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)$\\
 $ \promote{(\wid\Gamma, x :: \wid A)}$&$:=$&$(\promote{\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)$\\
 $ \promote{(\wid\Gamma, x \div \nar A)}$&$:=$&$(\promote{\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)$\\
 $ \promote{(\cdot)}$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}
\qquad
\begin{tabular}{rcl}
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x : \wid A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x \div \erase{\wid A})$\\
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x :: \wid A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x :: \wid A)$\\
 $ (\wid\Gamma, x \div \nar A)^\ominus$&$:=$&$(\wid\Gamma^\ominus, x \div \nar A)$\\
 $ (\cdot)^\ominus$&$:=$&$\cdot$\\
\end{tabular}\]

\begin{lemma}
\label{include.demote.eq.orig}
$\demote{(\ups\nar\Gamma)} = \nar\Gamma$
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{include.promote.eq.orig}
$\promote{(\ups\nar\Gamma)} = \nar\Gamma$
\end{lemma}


\begin{lemma}
\label{demote.pres}
If $\wprov \wid \Gamma \rctx$, then
$\nprov \demote{\wid \Gamma} \rctx$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}\ %
  \begin{itemize}
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\wid\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemma~\ref{erase.type})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\demote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad {\demote{\wid\Gamma}} \nprov \erase{\wid A} : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\demote{\wid\Gamma}}, x \div \erase{\wid A})\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \demote {\wid \Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\demote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad {\demote{\wid\Gamma}} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\demote{\wid\Gamma}}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\demote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad \ups (\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\demote{\wid\Gamma}}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \end{itemize}
  \cqed
\end{proof}

\begin{lemma}
\label{promote.pres}
If $\wprov \wid \Gamma \rctx$, then
$\nprov \promote{\wid \Gamma} \rctx$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}\ %
  \begin{itemize}
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\wid\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemma~\ref{promotion.weakening})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\promote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad \ups(\promote{\wid \Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\promote{\wid\Gamma}}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \demote {\wid \Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemma~\ref{narrow.weakening})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\promote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad {\promote{\wid\Gamma}} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\promote{\wid\Gamma}}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \item If we have
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
then we construct (using Lemmas~\ref{demotion.weakening} and~\ref{promotion.weakening})
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\promote{\wid\Gamma}} \rctx \qquad \ups (\promote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\promote{\wid\Gamma}}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
  \end{itemize}
  \cqed
\end{proof}



\subsection{Rules}

\subsubsection{Context Formation}

\[
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\wprov \cdot \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\justifies
\nprov \cdot \rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\wid\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \demote {\wid \Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]


\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\nar\Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups {\nar\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
Semantics:
\[
\begin{array}{rcl}
({\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A)^* &=& ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*)\\
({\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)^* &=& ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*})\\
({\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)^* &=& ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\nar A}^*)\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\sem{{\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A} &=& (\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*})\\
\sem{{\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A} &=& (\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*})\\
\sem{{\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A} &=& (\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\nar A}^*)\\
\end{array}
\]
\[
\begin{array}{rcl}
({\nar\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)^* &=& ({\nar\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*})\\
({\nar\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)^* &=& ({\nar\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\nar A}^*)\\
\end{array}
\]

\begin{lemma}[Demotion Weakening]
\label{demotion.weakening}
If $\ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov J$, then $\wid \Gamma \wprov J$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}[Promotion Weakening]
\label{promotion.weakening}
If $\wid\Gamma \wprov J$, then $\ups(\promote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov J$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}[Narrow Weakening]
\label{narrow.weakening}
If $\demote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov J$, then $\promote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov J$.
\end{lemma}


\begin{lemma}
\label{semantic.weakening}
For any $\wid \Gamma$, the context ${\wid \Gamma}^*$ is a subset of $\sem{\wid \Gamma}$.
Therefore any judgment that holds in context in ${\wid \Gamma}^*$ also holds in
$\sem{\wid \Gamma}$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{include.brackets.eq.star}
$\sem{\ups \nar \Gamma} = \nar \Gamma^*$
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{include.star.eq.star}
$(\ups \nar \Gamma)^* = \nar \Gamma^*$
\end{lemma}


\begin{lemma}
\label{demote.star.eq.star}
$(\demote{\wid \Gamma})^* = \wid \Gamma^*$
\end{lemma}

\begin{lemma}
\label{promote.star.eq.brackets}
$(\promote{\wid \Gamma})^* = \sem{ \wid \Gamma}$
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
By induction on $\wid \Gamma$, using Lemma~\ref{erase.star.eq.star}.
\cqed
\end{proof}


\begin{lemma}[Context Semantic Soundness]\ %
\label{semantic.soundness.context}
  \begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
\item If $\wprov {\wid\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov {{\wid\Gamma}}^*\rctx$.
\item If $\wprov {\wid\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov \sem{{\wid\Gamma}}\rctx$.
\item If $\nprov {\nar\Gamma}\rctx$, then $\prov {{\nar\Gamma}}^*\rctx$.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{lemma}


\begin{proof}\ %
\begin{itemize}
\item
We know
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\wid\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x : \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
and therefore
\[\prov \wid\Gamma^* \rctx \qquad \prov \sem{\wid\Gamma} \rctx\]
\[\wid\Gamma^* \prov \wid A^*:\rtype \qquad \sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x^*} \]
which is enough to show
\[\prov ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*) \rctx\qquad
\prov(\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*}) \rctx\]
\item
We know
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \demote {\wid \Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
and therefore
\[\prov \wid\Gamma^* \rctx \qquad \prov \sem{\wid\Gamma} \rctx\]
\[(\demote{\wid\Gamma})^* \prov \nar A^*:\rtype \]
which is enough to show (using Lemma~\ref{semantic.weakening} and Lemma~\ref{demote.star.eq.star})
\[\prov ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\nar A}^*) \rctx\qquad
\prov(\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\nar A}^*) \rctx\]
\item
We know
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\wprov {\wid\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}) \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\wprov ({\wid\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
and therefore
\[\prov \wid\Gamma^* \rctx \qquad \prov \sem{\wid\Gamma} \rctx\]
\[(\ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma}))^* \prov \wid A^*:\rtype \qquad \sem{\ups(\demote{\wid\Gamma})}, x^* : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x^*} \]
using Lemmas \ref{include.brackets.eq.star}, \ref{include.star.eq.star}, and~\ref{demote.star.eq.star} this is the same as
\[\wid\Gamma^* \prov \wid A^*:\rtype \qquad \wid\Gamma^*, x^* : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x^*} \]
which is enough to show (also using Lemma~\ref{semantic.weakening})
\[\prov ({\wid\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*}) \rctx\qquad
\prov(\sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*}) \rctx\]
\item
We know
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad {\nar\Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x \div \nar A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
and therefore
\[\prov \nar\Gamma^* \rctx \qquad \nar\Gamma^* \prov \nar A^*:\rtype \]
which is enough to show
\[\prov ({\nar\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\nar A}^*) \rctx\]
\item
We know
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\nprov {\nar\Gamma} \rctx \qquad \ups {\nar\Gamma} \wprov \wid A : \rtype
\justifies
\nprov ({\nar\Gamma}, x :: \wid A)\rctx
\end{prooftree}
\]
and therefore
\[\prov \nar\Gamma^* \rctx \]
\[ (\ups\nar\Gamma)^* \prov \wid A^*:\rtype \qquad \sem{\ups\nar\Gamma}, x^* : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x^*} \]
Using Lemmas~\ref{include.brackets.eq.star} and~\ref{include.star.eq.star} we get
\[ \nar\Gamma^* \prov \wid A^*:\rtype \qquad \nar\Gamma^*, x^* : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x^*} \]
which is enough to show
\[\prov ({\nar\Gamma}^*, x^* : {\wid A}^*, \sem x : \tsem {\wid A} {x^*}) \rctx\]
\end{itemize}
\cqed
\end{proof}

\subsubsection{Variable Rules}

\[
\begin{prooftree}
x : \wid A \in  \wid\Gamma
\justifies
\wid\Gamma \wprov x : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x :: \wid A \in  \wid\Gamma
\justifies
\wid\Gamma \wprov x : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
x \div \nar A \in  \nar\Gamma
\justifies
\nar\Gamma \nprov x : \nar A
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
x :: \wid A \in  \nar\Gamma
\justifies
\nar\Gamma \nprov x :  \erase {\wid A}
\end{prooftree}
\]

For the semantics we must check cases of \ref{semantic.soundness.term}. This is mostly straightforward, though
we need to invoke Lemma~\ref{erase.star.eq.star}.



\subsection{The Fiber Type}
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\ups\nar \Gamma \wprov \wid A : \wid\rtype \quad \nar \Gamma \nprov \nar M : \erase {\wid A}
\justifies
\nar \Gamma \nprov \pp {\nar M} {\wid A} : \nar\rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\ups {\nar \Gamma} \wprov \wid M : \wid A
\justifies
\nar \Gamma \nprov \{\wid M\} : \pp  {\erase{\wid M}} {\wid A}
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\demote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov \nar M : \erase{\wid A} \quad
\promote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov \nar N : \pp{\nar M}{\wid A}
\justifies
\wid\Gamma \wprov \epair{\nar M}{\nar N} : \wid A
\end{prooftree}
\]
In the elimination rule, $\wid A$ is a type over $\wid\Gamma$; the second premise
is well-formed because we can transport $\wid A$ to $\ups(\promote{\wid\Gamma})$ by
Lemma~\ref{promotion.weakening} and transport $\nar M$ to $\promote{\wid\Gamma}$ by Lemma~\ref{narrow.weakening}.


Definitional equality works like this. If $\nar \Gamma \nprov \nar N : \pp{\nar M}{\wid A}$ then
\[
  \nar N \equiv_\eta \{\epair{\nar M}{\nar N}\}
\]
and in general
\[
\epair{\nar M}{\{\wid N\}} \equiv_\beta \wid N
\]

\subsubsection{Semantics}
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
{\pp {\nar M} {\wid A}}^* &=& \tsem {\wid A} {\nar M^*}\\
\{\wid M\}^* &=& \sem {\wid M}\\
(\epair {\nar M} {\nar N})^* &=& {\nar M}^*\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\\
\\
\sem{\epair {\nar M}{\nar N}} &=& {\nar N}^*\\
\end{array}\]

Let's check that these are semantically sound.
In the formation rule, we know
\[\sem{\ups\nar\Gamma}, x : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x} : \rtype\]
\[\nar\Gamma^* \prov \nar M^* : \erase{\wid A}^*\]
Lemma~\ref{erase.star.eq.star} and Lemma~\ref{include.brackets.eq.star} says these are
\[\nar\Gamma^*, x : \wid A^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{x} : \rtype\]
\[\nar\Gamma^* \prov \nar M^* : \wid A^*\]
So substitute:
\[\nar\Gamma^* \prov \tsem{\wid A}{\nar M^*} : \rtype\]

For introduction, we must show
\[\nar \Gamma^* \prov \{\wid M\}^* : {\pp  {\erase{\wid M}} {\wid A}}^*\]
so
\[\nar \Gamma^* \prov \sem{\wid M} : \tsem{\wid A}{\wid M^*}\]
but this is exactly what we get out of the premise.

For elimination, we get from the premises (by Lemmas~\ref{demote.star.eq.star} and~\ref{promote.star.eq.brackets})
that
\[\wid\Gamma^* \prov \nar M^* : \wid A^* \]
\[\sem{\wid\Gamma} \prov \nar N^* : \tsem{\wid A}{\nar M^*}\]
and this is exactly what we need.

\subsection{The Glue Type}
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\demote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov \nar A : \nar\rtype \qquad
\promote{\wid\Gamma}, x \div \nar A \nprov \nar B : \nar\rtype
\justifies
\wid\Gamma \wprov \gg(x : \nar A).\nar B : \wid\rtype
\end{prooftree}
\qquad
\begin{prooftree}
\demote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov \nar M : \nar A \qquad
\promote{\wid\Gamma} \nprov \nar N : [\nar M/x]\nar B
\justifies
\wid\Gamma \wprov \bgel(\nar M, \nar N) : \gg(x : \nar A).\nar B
\end{prooftree}
\]
\[
\begin{prooftree}
\ups\nar\Gamma \wprov \wid M : \gg(x : \nar A).\nar B
\justifies
\nar\Gamma \nprov \bungel \wid M : [\erase{\wid M}/x]\nar B
\end{prooftree}
\]
Definitional equality works like this. If $\wid \Gamma \wprov \wid M : \gg(x : \nar A) . \nar B$ then
\[
 \wid M \equiv_\eta \bgel(\erase{\wid M}, \bungel \wid M)
\]
and in general
\[
\bungel(\bgel(\nar M,\nar N)) \equiv_\beta \nar N
\]

\subsubsection{Semantics}
\[\begin{array}{rcl}
(\gg(x : \nar A).\nar B)^* &=& \nar A^*\\
\bgel(\nar M,\nar N)^* &=& \nar M^*\\
(\bungel \wid M)^* &=& \sem{\wid M}\\
\end{array}
\qquad
\begin{array}{rcl}
\tsem{\gg(x : \nar A).\nar B}{M} &=& [M/x^*]\nar B^*\\
\sem{\bgel(\nar M,\nar N)} &=& \nar N^*\\
\\
\end{array}\]

Let's check that these are semantically sound.
In the formation rule, we know
\[ \wid\Gamma^* \prov \nar A^* : \rtype \]
\[ \sem{\wid\Gamma}, x^* : \nar A^* \prov \nar B^* : \rtype \]
which is exactly what we need to show.

For introduction, we know
\[ \wid\Gamma^* \prov \nar M^* : \nar A^*  \]
\[ \sem{\wid\Gamma} \prov \nar N^* : [\nar M^*/x^*]\nar B^* \]
which is exactly what we need to show.

For elimination, we know
\[\nar\Gamma^* \prov \sem{\wid M} : [\wid M^*/x^*]\nar B^*\]
which is exactly what we need to show.





